{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_emmental_ver01/data/sn83045293/00517012452/1920102701/0080.xml":{"full_text":"TWO\nCHURCHES OBSERVE M\u2019SWINEY DEATH\nUNIONISTS UND\nupimimsT\nopen emu\nPolishers Refuse Wage Cut\nand Walk Out.\nThe first open break between Mil\nwaukee labor and industry as a re\nsult of the tendency on the part of\nemployers to use unemployment and\nthe general business depression as a\nmeans to reduce, wages and break\n\u2022union standards became known to\n\u2022day with the lockout of the metal\npolishers force of the Milwaukee\nGas Specialtiy Co., 20th and Cly\n\u25a0fbourn Sts.\nAccording to Frank Oakley, busi\nness manager of the Metal Polishers\u2019\n'\u2022Union, the lockout followed the re\nfusal of the men to submit to a 10\n'per cent wage reduction. While for\nthe present only five men are effect\ned the entire shop force of between\n100 to 125 men and women may be\nInvolved shortly as the company has\ngplans to make the wage cut effective\nThroughout the plant.\nWage Cuts Made.\nOakley said that wage reductions\nmade in another plant and that\nthe metal polishers employed there\nWere likely to be called out within\nthe next 24 hours.\n\"Metal polishers are engaged In a\n\u2019jiiglily specialized trade and it is\nhighly signlflca\u201ent that skilled labor\nIs being submitted to the first at\ntempt at reduction,\u201d Oakley\nfraid. \"The scale paid at the Gfcs\nCo. was 95 cents an hour.\niAn increase of 10 percent was grant\ned the metal polishers last summer\nWnd the announcement which led to\njthe lockout was to the effect that\nJthis increase was to be taken away\nJfrom the men.\nOthers to Go Out.\n1 \"A similar announcement was\nsnade in another shop employing be-\nItween 10 and 12 metal polishers and\nit is not recalled by the company\nfthe men probably will be out by to\niiiight.\u201d\nIt was learned that the Gas Spe\ncialty Co., among others, employed\nex-prize fighter to scab on the\nlimen.\nI A meeting of the met&l polishers\nt&nion is scheduled for tonight at\n\u00a9atftenders\u2019 hall.\n60,000 Jobless In Detroit.\nBY NATE Li. WELCH.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe Federated Press.\nDETROIT \u2014The contention of la\nshor spokesmen that tens of thou\nsands of men were being discharged\n,jfrom the industrial plants of this\ni\u2019eity has been substantiated by no\n-less a person than Mayor Couzons,,\n'who is trying to relieve the situation.\nsHe declares that there are at least\ni;\u20ac0,000 men unemployed,\nPublic employment' is proposed\nby the mayor. City improvement\n'\u2022will be speeded up to provide Jobs\n\u2019/or the out of works and to relieve\ni Wage cutting is prevalent in near\nly all plant's. Union heads are being\n[informed that after contracts ex\npire there will be no further deal\nings with organized labor.\nf Should this situation come about\njW bitter struggle is imminent. Or\nganized labor is determined not to\nWield any of the gains secured\nthrough years of struggle.\nHAIL COMMISSION\n[REDUCES BENTS IN\ni FOOD CASES HERE\nBender, Chief of Bureau, Is\nAsked to Become Realtor.\nFour orders from the Rail com\nfrnission, reducing the rents of local\ntenants' on appeal to the rent bu\nreau, were received today by Paul\n(H. Pressintin, assistant arbiter.\nIn the case of Fred Strobel, vs.\niOtto Conrad, the rental for an up-\nJper flat at 708 Booth St., was cut\nFrom S3O to S2B a month, retroac\ntive to \u00a3yly 28.\nTn the case of W. H. Larkin \u2022'Vs.\npPaul Llmebarger, the rates for the\npremises at 518 Beulah Ave. were\nbut from S2B to s2l, retroactive to\nfcluly 3.\nWant Bender as Realtor.\nA. W. Schubert had his rent re\nduced to s2l. Fred Fent was de\nfendant. Schubert occupies a flat\nat 1223 22nd gt. The cut Is retroac\ntive to July 14.\nFollowing a two-hour discussion\nV>f the rent law and its enforce\nment, late yesterday, between Ar\nbiter Walter Bender and members\npf the Milwaukee Real Estate board,\nfche arbiter was extended an invita\ntion by J. W. Disch, secretary of the\nboard, to become an associate mem\njber.\n'\u2018Bonder\u2019s answers convinced the\nbealtor's that they can look for ab\nsolute fairness in the enforcement\nof the rent law/\u2019 Disch said, \u201cThe\nI\u2019ealtors understand thoroughly the\nobjects and provision of the law and\nI believe that the majority of them\nkre ready to offer full co-operation.\u201d\nExpect Reid Decision.\nA decision from the circuit court\nJyy attorneys for George J. Reid, at\ntacking the rent bureau's authority\nunder the state constitution, to en\nforce the rent law, is expected this\ntvetk, The case will probably be\ncarried to the Wisconsin supreme\ncourt lor Anal decision, it was in\ntimated.\nOn complaint of Claude Franklin,\nh tenant of the apartments at 146\nfcSrd St., against A. Knoeller, the\nbent was cut 15 per cent on seven\napartments. The reduction dates\n.back to April 1.\nWALSH WILLSPEAK\nHERE NEXT SUNDAY\nFrank P. Walsh of Kansas City,\nfchalrman of the federal commis\nsion on industrial relations, will\n\u00a3yteak in Milwaukee Sunday after\nnoon. He will speak in the interest\nas James Thompson's candidacy for\nKnited States senator against the\nEsch-Cummins law and the league\nof nations.\nWednesday, October 27, 1920.\nCHIEF JANSSEN\nMAY NOT FULLY\nREGAIN HEALTH j\n.\u00a3ffPflra|K:|f\u00bb\u00a7a\nChief of Police John T. Janssen,\nwho yesterday celebrated the com\npletion of 33 years as chief of the\nlocal \"finest,\u201d may never fully re\ncover from his recent illness, Dr.\nHarry T. Bradley, Janssen\u2019s physi\ncian, said today.\nJanssen was stricken about four\nmonths ago. At that time it was\nannounced that he had contracted\na severe cold at the Athletic park,\nwhile watching a ball game. About\na month ago, it was announced that\nJanssen was on the road to recovery,\nbut since that time he has reported\nfor ddty in the central police sta\ntion once or twice a week.\nJanssen has been on the police\nforce 43 years.\nTRADE SCHOOL\nGIRL CAN SHI\nKNEE-IN TUB\nHalf-Length Hose Are\nFrowned Upon Here.\nDimpled knees may be all right\nin their place, but Milwaukee trade\nschool girls will have to show them\nin the bath tub or wait until they\nare old enough to join a musical\n(fWnedy Tthorus. t\nOra Blanchard, principal 6f the\u201d\nGirl\u2019s Trade school, today an\nnounced that a ban had been placed\non the wearing of half-length hose\nin her institution.\n\"The custom will not be encour\naged here,\u201d she said. A few isolated\noases have appeared since the\nvogue came in, but we sat on them\nright away. Only yesterday a girl\nmade her appearance in a pair\u2014\nbut she isn\u2019t wearing them today.\u201d\nOn, the other hand, the fad seems\nto have escaped the local high\nschools, two principals even have\nadmitted that they do not know\nwhat they are.\nPrincipal A. C. Shong, West Di\nvision High school, declared he was\nnot acquainted with half hose and\nso couldn\u2019t comment.\n\u201cI don\u2019t know what they are,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cI never have had them\nbrought to my attention. If they\nare anything like what children\nwear, they certainly are not mod\nest.\u201d\nGustave A. Fritsche,\nBay View High. school, pleaded\nequal Ignorance of what half hose\nconstituted, confining himself to a\nstatement that he would have to\nbe shown an example first before he\ncould make any comment.\nCITY T 0 G(fOVER TOP IN\nSALVATIONIST CAMPAIGN\nThat Milwaukee easily will go\nover the top In the Salvation army\ncampaign for $70,000 for the pro\nposed rescue mission and other char\nitable work, was the assertion last\nnight of A. T. Van Scoy, chairman\nof the state advisory board of the\narmy. A survey of the. state is to be\nmade shortly to determine the most\nlogical place for the erection of tho\nmission, according to Van Scoy. Sta\ntistics of need in various counties\nwill be the chief, factor of the sur\nvey.\nPARTY MEETS\nTONIGHT.\nSouth Side Turn hall. National\nAve., near 3rd Ave, Speakers,\nDaniel W T Hoan, Henry G. Heller\nmaiui, Mabel Search and William\nF. Quick.\nTOMORROW NIGHT.\nBurleigh Theater, between 9th\nanti 10th Sts., 8 p. m, Speaker Vic\ntor L. Berger.\nHite Theater, Green Bay Am\nnntl Ring St. Speaker, 8 p. m\u201e Daniel\nW. Hoan. 9:15 p. in,, Victor L. Berg\ner.\nOdd Fellow's hall, Klnnfeklnnlc'\nand Potter Ave.. 8 p. m. Speakers,\nRobert Buech. Daniel W. Hoan. and\nJoseph Padway.\nBonk's hall, 719 Ist Ave.. 8 p. m.\nSpeakers, Robert Bffech, Edwin W.\nKnappo, and Casimir Kowalski.\nRusse\u2019s hall, 24th and Lincoln\nAvenues. 8 p. m. Speakers, Edwin\nW. Knappo, Leo Krzycki, and\nThomas Duncan.\nHarmonic hall, Ist Ave. and Min\neral St., 8 p. m. Speakers. Leo\nKrzycki. Henry G. Hellermann, and\nJo lx* Ermcnc.\nFACTORY MEETS TOMORROW\nNOON\nNash Motors Co., Oklahoma near\nClement, R, Buech, W. Buech.\nN. W. Malleable Iron Co., 758\nPark St.. Duncan Franklin.\nYilter Mfg. Co.. 915 Clinton St.,\nKnappo. Rutkowski\nSivyer Steel Casting Co., 37th\nA v e\u201e Gaucr, Bncr.\nWorden-Mien Co.. Port Washing\nton Road. Richter, Padway.\nCutler-Hammer Co., st. Paul Ave.,\nKrzycki, Hampel.\nJOHN T. JANSSEN.\nBUSINESS FIRMS\nPREPARING FUR\nDROP IN IRADE\nSale of Xmas Goods Already\non at Present.\nBusiness firms of Milwaukee are\nmaking preparations for the possi\nbility of a business depression in\nthe near future., according to V.\nM. Pace, sales manager, Gimbel\nBrothers, today.\nPace said:\nThe prices of our goods have\ncut down so low that we\nMe hardly making any profit.\nThis is done to reduce the stock\nwe now have on hand. Because\nthis is a presidential year and be\ncause there is industrial depres\nsion looming up, we are taking\nall precaution! possible to avert\ntrouble when the worst comes.\nSales Are Big.\nBecause of our price cut we\nhave had the largest sales in the\nhistory of the store for this time\nOf year. We have started our\nChristmas drive earlier this year\nas it may be harder to make sales\nafter eelction. As the banks are\ntight now it is almost impossible\nto borrow funds from them to\ntide over a poor period.\nBecause of these things we are\ndoing all we can to protect our\nselves from any trouble in the fu\nture. Wi* are trying to insure our\nyequilibriufn in case the worst\ncomes\nIt was announced today by\nGeorge Berg, manager Gridley Dairy\nCo., that more milk is being stolen\nfrom porches after delivery than\never before. The police lay this\ncondition to the large number of\nunemployed a sshown by figures\ngiven out by the United States em\nployment bureau.\nFINDINGS\nBY\nVICTOR L. BERGER\nContinued From First Page.\nThe Bolshevik terror was the re\nsult of the Czarist terror.\nthe Socialist party dur\ning the last year has not at all\ngained in membership outside of\nWisconsin \u2014and this is due to\nthe activities of the various Com\nmunistic organizations on one\nend \u2014and the Farmer-Labor ag\ngregation and thre Non-Partisan\nFarmers League on the other\na poll of The Literary Digest\namong 600,000 voters in the piv\notal states of New York, New\nJersey, Ohio, Indiana, Illinois\nand California shows which way\nthe wind is blowing.\nThe returns foreshadow vic\ntory for Harding in all of these\nstates. It will be an election by\n\u201cdisgust\u201d\u2014by disgust with Wil\nson and the Democratic party.\ni?\nBesides this, any one who is\ncurious as to the effect of repres\nsion on the Radical vote will be\ninterested in the strong swing\ninto the Socialist column. \"The\nfigures of our poll,\u201d says The\nDigest, \u201creveal a striking in\ncrease in the Socialist vote,\nwhich seems to be about doubled\nin Indiana and Ohio, tripled in\nNew Jersey, Illinois and Califor\nnia, and almost multiplied by five\nin New York, where the Socialist\nassemblymen were unseated.\nA further evidence of a\ncertain drift away from the old\nparties is the vote of .1,331 for\nChristensen, the Farmer-Labor\ncandidate.\u201d\n\nThe ousting of the assembly\nmen did the trick in New York.\nAnd the slur of the Fifth district\nmust react in Wisconsin, where\nthe Socialists have a fairly good\norganization\u2014where there is no\nChristensen ticket in the field\u2014\nand where there is absolutely no\ndanger of Cox carrying even a\nsingle county of the 71 in the\nstate.\nAny man or woman who want\u00a3\nto put in an effective protest\nagainst the present conditions\ncan do so only by voting the So\ncialist ticket.\nBoth old parties were a unit\nfor the war. Both old parties\nwere a unit to pass the Espion\nage Act and other laws of op\npression and suppression.\nBoth old parties were a unit to\nreturn the railroads to private\nHORNING IN ON THE NEWS\nl Mil w a u kee's 1\nJ east side proses\n-5 sional tourists to-\nIday were prepar-\u2022\nI ing to flit to the\nI southland, leav-j\nling the pleasures\n,of fall vain and j\n-j winter snow to\nI the workers here.\ngjflJ\nIJgSk v\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER\nIRISH FREEDOM FRIENDS\nHERE DESIRE TO PLACE\nFLOWER SPRAY ON BIER\nDeath is Murder Attributable to Lloyd George for Which He\nMust Answer, Says Local Organiza\ntion Head.\nAll of the Catholic churches in\nMilwaukee will hold services of\nindignation and sorrow at the\nmurder of Lord Mayor Mac-\nSwiney, according to Andrew J.\nClarke, president of the local or\nganization of the Friends of Free\ndom, today.\nSaid Clarke:\nYesterday the local organization\nof the Friends of Irish Freedom\ncabled to Dublin to arrange for\nthe placing of a wreath on the bier\nof the late Lord Mayor at the\nfuneral Thursday. If the British\ngovernment allows a decent burial\nfor MacSwlney, which I believe\nthey will, the wreath will be one\nof many sent by friends of Ire\nland from this country\nIrish Want Quiet.\nSpecial services will be held\nSunday in all of Catholic churches\nof Milwaukee and if possible, a\nprocession led by a band will be\nheld.\nEvery paper in Ireland is daily\nwarning the peoole to keep quiet\nand not resort to force.\nThis seems to be lived up to in\nall places. True, we hear of a po\nliceman being killed once in. a\nwhile, but that occurs in New\nYork and Chicago every day, only\nIreland can have headlines when\nit comes to such things, while the\n-police of this country cannot. It is\nput into discredit as much as pos\nsible the passive resistance of the\nIrish people.\nDeath Is Murder.\nThere is some questsion as to\nwhether MacSwiney\u2019s death was\nsuicide. If it had been suicide the\nchurch would have nothing to do\nwith his remains nor would a\nNot Torture, Only College\nFreshmen \u201cGetting Theirs\u201d\nLife of Fledglings Miserable\nSince Loss of Glass\nRush.\nIf you pass the Marquette \"frat\u201d\nhouses some quiet evening and hear\nan unearthly yell ofllowede by the\nappearance of a partly disrobed fig\nure, that \u201cscoots\u201d across the lawn\nInto another building, perhops fol\nlowed by half a dozien determined\npersons, or, if you see some pink\ncheeked ingenious looking youth,\nhis coat on inside out, his trousers\npulled up above the knees, and his\nhair clipped, or clinging to the up\npermost branches of a tree, don\u2019t\nbecome excited, it is only fun.\nIt is what is known in college par\nlanse as the \"ego message.\u201d\nHe is geting his \"milk\u201d\u2014the milk\nof knowledge, and it is only through\nthe offices of his heriditary enemy,\nthe sophmore, that he can have ac\ncess to this sacred drink.\nFreshies Lost Rush.\nIt would not have been so ,had\nthe freshman been endowed with a\n.little more \"elbow greese\u201d at the\nclass rush, but since they fell down\nmiserably, it is said, they are com\npelled to accept the consequences.\nUnder the class rush rules of Mar\nquette\u2014which are \"tame\u201d compared\nto those of eastern colleges \u2014the\nPOLICE DRAG RIVER FOR\nSAILOR WHO VANISHED\nPolice and coast guards today\nwere dragging the Menomonee\nriver at the foot of 16th St., on re\nport that a sailor on the steamer\nHarvey D. Boulder had fallen over\nboard. The missing man is Leon An\nderson, a deck hand. The Boulder\ncame to Milwaukee from Toledo\nyesterday with coal.\nownership. After the govern\nment had spent a billion and a\nhalf \u2014to put them in better shape\nthey return them to the capitalist\nexploiters with a guarantee.\nBoth parties were a unit to\nkeep me out of Congress, and\nkeep out the Socialists in New\nYork\nBoth parties are a unit in de\nmanding representative govern\nment for themselves only\u2014for\nthe capitalist class only.\nAnd both old parties are a\nunit to keep E. V. Debs, the\ncandidate of the Socialist party,\nin prison while the campaign is\non.\nBoth old parties must there\nfore be considered a unit when\nthe voters visit their condemna\ntion upon them.\nI Prominent lo-\nj cal home brewers j\nj today are looking\ngj for places to j\nI* store an extra\nI supply of the in-\n\"gredients follow-\niii g aimounee\nagent that the\ngovernment i s\nl after hops and\nI malt.\nW r\n>lllll\n1 Xu\npriest have been in attendance all\nof the time he was fasting.\nTt is murder by England and\nperhaps some day Lloyd George\nmay be tried for his terrible\ncrime. Lord C&stlereagh who was\nas oppressor of Ireland commit\nted suicide but\u201e the Irish will\nnever allow Lloyd George that\npleasure, they will convict him of\nmurder in this affair and hang\nhim to a post. He has been in\ndicted for murder once already\nand has his freedom and auto\ncratic powers, when he is tried by\nthe Irish he will suffer for the\ncrime and oppression he has\nplaced on Ireland.\nWorse Than Cromwell.\nWhy, the persecution of Lloyd\nGeorge puts to shame the das\ntardly crimes of Cromwell and\nCastlereagh.\nWhere .are Taft, Wickersham,\nButler and all other great Ameri\ncans? Nicholas Murray Butler,\nwho cried so loudly for the women\nand children of Br-lgium? 'Why\ndoesn\u2019t he listen to the wailings of\nIreland? What will America do\nfor the oppressed human beings in\nIreland? Will they sit by and let\nthe cruel heel of British autocracy\nstamp out the people as a race?\nOther societies are preparing to\ntake up the case of MacSwiney. At\nits meeting Friday night in Alham\nbra hall, 4th S\u2019t. and Grand Ave., the\nG. U. G. Germania, Wisconsin\u2019s\nlargest fraternal risk society, will\nconsider a resolution to be intro\nduced by Fred Weingart.\nCondcmes British R ll le.\nThe resolution condemns British\noppressions in Ireland, demands\nthat America recognize the Irish\nrepublic, and expresses sympathy\nfor the widow of the martyr of\nCork.\nWhen the society holds its thea\nter benefit in the Alhambra and\nNew Strand Nov. 1-5, Secretary\nCharles Wolf probably will ask that\nat least one number be devoted to\nthe MacSwiney affair.\nOther German American societies\nare preparing to take up the Mac-\nSwiney case, it is understood.\n\"freshies,\u201d if they had won tjie rush,\nwould have been thereafter absolved\nfrom wearing the Marquette jazz\ncap, a round, two colored affair that\nfits the cranium as a cork does a\nsoda bottle.\nThe freshies lost, of course, and\nsome wore mad. They wouldn\u2019t\nwear the caps. Sophs have a way,\nhowever, of punishing the recaltr'i\ncant and that\u2019s why some have their\nhair clipped, some wear their clothes\ninside .out and some don\u2019t wear any\nclothes at all\u2014down in the cellars\nof the fraternity houses.\nFight Toothpick Duel.\nIn the. east they do not only de\nprive a freshie of his clothes, but\ngive him a bath under the pump,\n:n the sink or in the campus foun\ntain.\nIf th\u00a9 freshie persists in his \"in\ncorrigibility\u2019 there are other things\nthat they will be called upon to do,\ndepending upon the ingenuity of the\nmembers of the hazing body. He\nmay be called upon to chase him\nself around the rlf of a flower bed\nuntil he has overtaken himself, or\nnumbers of the freshies may be\nseated, one behind another and, with\ntoothpicks for oars, told to row up\nthe library steps. Or he may be\ntaken out upon v thoroughfare, and\nwith a match stick for a weapon, be\nmade to stage a duel with another\nvictim with all the punctilio of the\nFrench code.\nMEET TO PROTEST\nSAVAGE TROOPS\nON GERMAN LAND\nInvitation Is Extended to All\nPersons Interested.\nA mass meeting protesting the\nquartering of French Sengal troops\non the occupied sections of Ger\nmany will be held in the Pabst thea\nter, Monday night. All persons\ninterested, irrespective of race or\ncreed .are urged to attend.\nThe meeting was planned for the\npurpose of urging upon congress\nthe necessity of protesting the many\noutrages committed upon women\nand children in that section by\nthese troops.\nThe call has been signed by many\nprominent Milwaukeeans including\nMayor Daniel W. Hoan, Archbishop\nS. Q. Messmer, the Rev, W. W.\nKennerley, the Rev. Morris Eversz,\nthe Rev. William T. Dorward, the\nRev. M. J. H. Albrecht, the Rev,\nJohn. F. La\u00dfoule, Otto P. Seifriz,\nJoseph P. Oallan, Adolph C. Dick,\nAlbert O. Trostel, O. A. Olsen, and\nmany others.\nThe list of speakers has not been\ncompleted. It will be announced\nlater.\nAUTOIST FINED SSO.\nJohn Biedenblnder was fined SSO In\ndistrict court today on the charge of reck\nless driving. It is alleged that he drove\nhis car onto the curb at 18th and Cherry\ngts and knocked over a fire hydrant.\ngf\u00abJ Jf>g\nY A\nA\n\u25a0l The rush for i\n1 heavy overcoats 1\nI was on in earnest j\nI today following i\nagreement by zoo\nR and siui spot!\nB weather prophets\nE that it is going\ni to he a long,\ngj chilly winter in j\n1 these parts. J\nREO GROSS HAS\n100 NEW POST\nWAR CHARGES\nClaims Come From Cases De-\nveloped Since Discharge.\nDespite the fact that the war has\nbeen over for more than two years,\nthe home section of the Red Cross is\nhandling 100 new claims for com\npensation from men who have de\nveloped tuberculosis and mental ail\nments since their discharge from the\narmy.\nThis was revealed this afternoon\nwith the reading of the report of the\nRed Cross at the annual meeting of\nthe state organization in the City\nclub.\nAided 7,431 Families.\nDuring the fiscal year of Oct. 1,\n1919, to Oct. 1, 1920, 7,431 families\nwere given assistance by the Red\nCross, 1,771 families being taken\ncare of in Milwaukee county alone.\nThe expenditures aggregated $45,-\n196.46, of which $17,159.56 were for\nloans.\nThe work in the city is confined\nto service to disabled mfen and to\nthe adjustment of claims for dis\ncharged soldiers.\nDuring the summer, 316 children\nwere given diplomas for completion\nof swimming courses.\nDuring state fair week, the first\naid station at the fair handled 192\ncases.\nForm Disaster Unit.\nThe third Red Cross roll call,\nwhich was conducted in December,\nresulted in a chapter membership of\n49,712 and 1,968 magazine subscrib\ners. Pledges amounting to $122,000,\nof which $119,105.34 has already\nbeen collected were received.\nMilwaukee has also Recently or\nganized a depot for disaster relief\nunits. The equipment, which con\nsists of cot, blankets, clothing and\nis sufficient to take care\nof 100 persons.\nFEDERAL GRAND JURY\nMEETS HERE TO WEIGH\nLIQUOR SALE EVIDENCE\nContinued From First Page.\nthe law would fail of its purpose un\nless impartially enforced.\nThe Jury comprises:\nS. G. Courteen, foreman; H. A. Schluch\nbier, Beaver Dam; William Weber, Keno\nsha; Charles Pruetz, Hustisford; T. Berger\nKenosha: William Fink. Sommers; Fred\nBrosie, Manitowoc; Walter Nimz, Mani\ntowoc; William .Tecque, Port Washington;\nR. H. Blrdsoll. Racine; William Schwart,\nShel/ovgan; William Braach. Sheboygan;\nCarl Sabath, Eagle; William Gruhle, Bar\nton; E. F. Russel, Hartford; James Sheri\ndan, Menomonee Falls, and S. A. Bartlett,\nD. K. Portemay, Walter Gregg, E. A.\nHuebner. Louis Hlrsch, Arthur W. Rieson,\nMilwaukee.\nFire Discloses Still.\nHeitler, In his alleged confession,\nis declared to have made sensational\ndisclosures, and detailed the activi\nties of federal officials throughout\nthe country, state officials, mayors\nof small towns adjacent to Chicago,\npolice officers and patrolmen, deputy\nsheriffs and otheps. He declared\nhimself \u201cout of the business,\u201d but\nsaid he was ready to tell all he knew,\nand that he knew all about the op\nerations of the alleged rings.\nThe fire department -was called to\n556 Garden St., last night. They\nfound a fire which started when a\n50-gallon still exploded, a 10 and 12-\ngallon still, 300 gallons of moon\nshine and 50 gallons of mash. Ac\ncording to the police reports the\nbuilding is owned by Joseph Lega,\nand was occupied by Michael Jamsi\nzewskl. Folice authorities have not\nbeen able to find either man.\nKilled By Sleuths.\nJohn Chapusio, Hurley saloonlst,\nwas \"unlawfully killed by gun\nshots fired by federal officers acting\nunder direction of Group Chief Leo\nJ. Grove, J. T. Brereton, Victor J.\nDowd, William Knourek, Arthur Q.\nScully and Jay H. Sweeney.\u201d\nThis is the text of a verdict by\nthe coroner\u2019s jury in Hurley late\nyesterday. Chapusion was killed\nOct. 9 when a motor caravan, al\nlegedly loaded with whisky, was\nlambushed and fired upon by federal\nprohibition agents 15 miles south\nof Hurley.\nFollowing the return of the ver\ndict Attorney Myron Reed an\nnounced that he would tfflce up the\nshooting with Gov. Phillip and ask\nthe state authorities for co-opera\ntion before he took further action.\nSays Bribe Asked.\nGust Castagna, caught with a\nliquor cargo after the shooting, said\nthat he was urged by one of the\nfederal men to go to Milwaukee to\npurchase whisky. Peter Verich,\nowner of the Moose saloon, Hurley,\ntestified that a man told him that\n\"if you got a couple hundred dol\nlars we can fix it up with .your car\nso that you won\u2019t have, to go to\nJail.\"\nThat the \"home-brew restriction\nruling\u201d published in local news\npapers yesterday is just \"newspa\nper talk\u201d was the assertion of Mil\nwaukee brewers today.\nThey claitn that what is con\ntained in the ruling, as regards the\nmanufacture of a produce contain\ning not more than one-half of one\nper cent of alcohol, was originally\nincorporated in the 18th amend\nment.\nLaugh at Home Brew Rule.\n\u201cDon\u2019t pay any attention to it,\u201d\nsaid Henry Starke, secretary of the\nPabst Brewing Co. \u2018\u2018That\u2019s, all\nnewspaper talk. We knew all\nj S 7\nOffice girls and\nsalesladies are\npreparing a cam\npaign of \u201ccarry\nyour own milk\u201d\nfolio w i n g tlr\nfining of several\nrestauranteurs on\ncharges of selling\nadulterated milk.\nWednesday, October 27, 1920.\nHALLOWE\u2019EN\nHere's What Real Boys Willi\nDo on the Night of\nNights.\nWatch your windows, wire up your\ngates and take the ash box into the\ncellar. Hallowe\u2019en falls due Sat\nurday and the \"kids\u201d are planning\na rumpus.\nHere is what the cub reporter\nfound out today when, disguised as\na newsie, he frequented the haunts\nof the plotters:\n\u201cW e\u2019re gonna nail old man Brem\nan\u2019s door shut,\u201d related Norman\nAgathon, %03 Bartlett St. \"Won\u2019t he\nswear blue streaks though! The\ngang\u2019s gona roll one of the old\nwagons in the lot down into the\nriver, too. Gee! but there\u2019ll be a\nsplash!\n\u201cI\u2019m gonna soap windows and ring\ndoor bells,\u201d said the more timid John\nSqhmidt, 538 11th Si. He wouldn\u2019t\nsay more, perhaps knowing that the\nDetention home is only, across the\nstreet from where he lives.\n\u2018jWe\u2019re gonna dress up in spook\u2019s\nclothes,\u201d said \"Bill\u201d Baumgardt, 46S\nPotter Ave. \"We\u2019ll ring doorbells\nand raise a rumpus on the street.\nAfter that we\u2019re going over to r.\nkid\u2019s house and have a party. Oh!\nboy.\u201d\n\"There\u2019s a coupla of gates and a\nhalf dozen ash boxes we got a grudge\nagainst in our alley,\u201d explained Paul\nHaske, 2504 Walnut St., and we\u2019d\nlike ta even up. They say ya can\u2019t\ndo those things though this year,\nand it\u2019ll be pretty hard on tho\nbunch. Tough, ain\u2019t it when a fel\nler can\u2019t do nothing anymore.\u201d\nlILIUKEEAN\nSEEKS PIRATE\nPIRATE GOLD\nWith Expedition Searching for\nThompson Treasure.\nBound for Cocos Island, in search\nof pirate gold thought to have been\nburied there \"Bugs\u201d Thompson and\nBenito Bonito, both of whom flew\nthe Jolly Roger, is Merrill Trevis,\nMilwaukee, who, more than eight\nyears ago lived at 2303 Prairie St.\nTrevis is a member of the expedi\ntion, beaded by John McGrath, New\nYork, whose ship Saturday slipped\nsecretly out of \"an Atlantic -ort\u201d\nbound for the island of romance in\nquest of a treasure estimated at\nmore than $21,000,1)00.\nDepentl On Engineer.\nIt is upon Andrew B. Cullen,\nHalleybury, Conn., that the success\nof the expedition depends. While\nprospecting in the Ontario wilder\nness, Cullen claims he invented a\ndivining rod which will point in\nfallibly to ore deposits or buried\ncoins. Cullen refuses to divulge\nexactly how the rod will work.\nAccording to the best authenti\ncated tradition, the Cocos Island\ntreasure consists of $12,000,000 in\nmoney, plate jewels and cathedral\nornaments stolen from Lima in the\nearly part of the 19th century, dur\ning the wars of Simon Bolivar, by\n\u201cBugs\u201d Thompson. Thompson at\nthat time was skipper of the brig\nMary Dear, London. In addition,\nthere is $9,000,000 in bar gold, pig\nsilver and pieces of eight looted on\nthe Soanish main by Bonito, the\nlast of the \u201cgreat\u201d pirates.\nWas On Tuscarora.\nOnly one expedition, which visited\nthe Cocos Island in 1844 succeeded\nin obtaining any loot. Thompson\ndied at the home of a man named\n'Keating in Newfoundland and be\nqueathed him a chart of the island.\nKeating and Capt. Bogue sailed to\nCocos ano Keating came back with\nSIO,OOO in gold and jewels. During\nthe expedition, the crew mutinied\nand Bogtie lost his life under mys\nterious circumstances. Keating es\ncaped from the island in an open\nboat\nSince then many expeditions have\nfailed.\nTrevis for a while was on board\nthe revenue cutter Tuscarora. After\nthat, he went east and during the\nwar was in the United States navy.\nPLAN HARVEST BALL.\nThe Austrian-Hungarlan K. IT. Vereln\nwill hold a harvest ball In the large Lie\ndertafel hall, 7th and Prairie Sts., Satur\nday, Nov. 6.\n2 MORE DAYS\n\u201cOnly two more days to do\nyour registering for the Novem\nber 2 ejection.\u201d\nThis was the warning given to\nday by Robert Sehuffenhauer, So\ncialist member, city election com\nmission, for the benefit of women\nwho have not yet enrolled and\nfor men who contemplate voting\nip Milwaukee for the first time\nin the corning election.\nSchuffenhauer directed atten\ntion to the fact that registration\nWill close Friday at 10 p. m., as\nserting persons may register any\ntime before that hour in the\ncommission\u2019s office, second floor,\ncity hall, or on the main floor of\nthe municipal building, \u2019where\nclerks have been stationed in an\nticipation of a \u201clast minute\u201d rush.\nabout the ruling when prohibition\nfirst went into effect and have acted\nin-accordance with it.\u201d\n\u201cThere is nothing new about the\nhome urew ruling,\" declared J. G.\nSchmidt, officer of the Schlitz Brew\ning Co. \u201cIt has always been per\nmitted that a brew of one-half of\none per cent could be made. The\nmalt syrup we make and sell is not\ncapable of producing more than\nthat percentage of alcohol.\u201d\nI\u2019nder section 18 of the pro\nhibition act, only such brew as ex\nceeds one-half of one per cent is\nforbidden, according to Prohibition\nInspector Nelson A. White. Deal\ners and manufacturers w ho pro\nduce or sell a product that when\nbrewqd develops more than that\npercentage are liable to prosecution\nunder the act, he said.\nSOCIALISTS IN\nMADISON KEPT\nEAGOFFSTATE\nProtests agsftnst the present or\nder and flagrant violations of the\nconstitution, as well as the holding\nof Socialist meetings would have\nbeen impossible if Socialist legisla\ntors had not been present in Madi\nson to kill the Nye bill last year, Ed\nwin Knappe, Socialist candidate for\ndistrict attorney told an audience in\nHarmonie hall last night.\nThe gathering also was addressed\nby Sheriff Robert Buech, candidate\nfor congress, 4th district, and Jo\nseph A. Pad way. Aid. Thomas Rey\ni nolds presided.\nPadway exposed old party tactics\nwhich, he said, had always been to\ndodge the really important prob\nlems and use the least significant but\nmost involved question as a cam\npaign issue.\n\"They have made the league of\nnations the issue of this campaign,\nj Why, President. Wilson became sick\nI trying to explain it to the people.\nI Tvffiat will happen to the ordinary\nI man who should attempt to under\nstand it? It makes no difference\nI whether Article X remains in the\ntreaty or not, if capital wants war\nthere will be war.\ni \"Why don\u2019t the old party candi\ndates talk about, the peace time so\nj dition acts they intend to inflict upon\nthis country? Such laws are now\nin the making, laws under which\nany act of hate against a govern\nernment official could be interpreted\nas sedition and the writer of a polit\nical article or the designer of a car\ntoon convicted and sentenced to a\nprison term.\u201d\nAs examples of what a capitalistic\ngovernment, whether it be Repub\nlican or Democrat, is likefy to do in\nits attempt to stop the spread of\nradicalism, Pad way cited the cases\nof thi Washington correspondents of\nThe Federated Press and the treat\nment accorded them by Secretary\nColby, and traced the connection be\ntween these cases and the eviction\nj of E. J. Costello,, manager of Tn*t\nj Federated Press, from England.\nThe speaker also quoted figures\nfrom the official records, showing\nI the war waste indulged in by a Dem\nj ocratic administration and condoned\nj hy Republican and Democratic con\n-1 gressmen and senators alike.\nYou may ask what a Socialist con\n-1 gressman or two can accomplish in\nWashington. If Berger and Buech\nhad been down there when this\ngrafting was going on they could\nhave turned the light on It and I\ndoubt ver> much that it would havu\nbeen attempted.\nI \"P\u2019ear of disclosure undoubtedly\nI was one of the prime reasons why\nthey refused to seat Berger. The\nquestion is now whether the citizens\nof this county are to indorse viola\ntion of the principle of representa\ntive government or whether they will\nrebuke it. Not alone should the vot\ners qf the sth district send Berger\nback a third time, but the men and\nwomen of the 4th district should\nsend Robert Buech with him to\nmake Washington dictators under\nstand that American freedom is aliva\nin Wisconsin.\u201d\nChairman Reynolds urged voters\nto register in the few days remain\ning before election and on Nov. 2\nindorse the party which alone can bo\nrelied on to defend the rights of\nthe common people.\nSALE\nON ARMY WRIST\nWATCHES\nFor Milwaukee and Vicinity\nHa\nGuaranteed\nM 20 YEARS\nCjL JEWELED\nT; t ADJUSTED\nPrice During The War *ls\nA Chance to Purchase a\nWrist Watch Really\nCheap.\nTaking Into consideration that there\nwere more than one thousand dealer*\nafter this lot of Army Watches much\ncredit Is due our manager for his un\ntiring efforts in securing them, which\nnumber many thousands and give to\nthis firm the exclusive sale for theso\nwatches in Milwaukee. During the war\nthese rugged little timepieces could not\nbe made fast enough to supply the\nUnited States Army at 815.00 each.\nEvery movement is beautifully jmve'ed\nand adjusted and so marked with th#\nnumber of jewels and adjustmc as\nrequired by the United States Govern\nment. Every one has twep oxintuwd\nml passed by the Government inspeo*\nTors. So there can be no\nFurthermore, this firm\u2019s guarantee goes\nwith every one for 20 years. We now\noffer them for sale at $4.00 each, with\nthe distinct understanding jfhat th*\nmoney (every cent of it) will be Tp>\nfunded if watches as good as these o|\nany particular 